SSyynnooppssiiss
       ldapstart all

       ldapstart -d number

       ldapstart -i id

       ldapstart boot

DDeessccrriippttiioonn
       The  ldapstart  command  starts  daemons using information
       from the file.  ldapstart  checks  if  the  daemon  to  be
       started has any replicas.  If it does, then ldapstart will
       also start a process.

       ldapstart boot is used by the script  /etc/init.d/ldap  to
       start up the LDAP daemons at init 2.

   OOppttiioonnss
       Starts  all  the  daemons  listed in the /etc/ldap/ldaptab
       file.  Starts a particular daemon from the  ldaptab  file,
       where number corresponds to the number-th daemon listed in
       ldaptab.  Starts a  particular  daemon  from  the  ldaptab
       file,  where id corresponds to the identifier field in the
       ldaptab file.  Starts all bootable daemons. That is,  this
       option  starts all daemons in the ldaptab file that have a
       ``yes'' entry in the start at the ``boot'' field.

FFiilleess
       /etc/ldap/ldaptab
       /etc/init.d/ldap

